WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.040
Welcome everyone. Thanks for being here. I get to talk to you about a package called

00:00:12.040 --> 00:00:17.680
Censored. It's a new tidymodels package for survival models. And when people hear survival

00:00:17.680 --> 00:00:24.639
analysis, they often think of situations and data like this. And I mean, it's called survival

00:00:24.639 --> 00:00:32.720
analysis for a reason. But even though most examples are indeed like category time to

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:38.720
death, that is not the only context in which you might encounter censored data and hence

00:00:38.759 --> 00:00:46.759
a need for survival models. And I came across my favorite example for censored data. Before

00:00:46.759 --> 00:00:51.560
I joined RStudio, I was working at a data science consultancy. And one of my colleagues

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:58.680
chatted to me about his latest project. And that involved a newspaper company, which wanted to

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:04.480
know how many copies they should deliver to various outlets. And he was sort of musing that

00:01:05.639 --> 00:01:10.760
if there are any copies left, at the end of the day, they wouldn't know how many had been taken

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:17.199
and what the demand for the paper was. If there were none left, they would also still know how

00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:22.959
many were taken, but they wouldn't really know what the demand was and how many more could have

00:01:22.959 --> 00:01:28.599
would have been taken if they hadn't run out. So in that case, their observation of the newspaper

00:01:28.599 --> 00:01:35.279
demand is actually censored. It's capped at the numbers of papers that they provided. So this

00:01:35.279 --> 00:01:41.680
stats nerd in me grinned and was like, I suggest you look at survival analysis. And now I get to

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:47.959
tell you basically the same thing too. So if you have data of this format, where you're observing

00:01:47.959 --> 00:01:58.440
something until an event, be that time to death or newspapers taken until demand situation, and you

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:06.279
may or may not actually observe that event, please use survival analysis. That is designed to take

00:02:06.279 --> 00:02:11.000
both of these aspects into account. So if you take that data and shove it into a regular regression

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:19.360
model and model the time or the demand without taking that event indicator into account, you're

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:25.960
treating the observations as complete, when in fact they may just be incomplete. And if you're

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:31.839
dropping all of your censored observations and model the rest, you're also throwing away information

00:02:31.839 --> 00:02:39.440
and you're treating these observations as missing, while they are actually just incomplete. So survival

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:45.479
analysis is an important field of modeling and we're extending support for it in tidy models. The

00:02:45.479 --> 00:02:53.119
first milestone in this are the models themselves, to be able to specify them, fit them and

00:02:53.119 --> 00:03:00.600
predict with them. And you may well be aware that R has an abundance of riches in different models

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:08.720
contributed by different people, and it also has nearly the same abundance of riches in interfaces

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:14.679
to these models. And as you just heard, tidy models wants to make it effective, safe and

00:03:14.679 --> 00:03:21.160
ergonomic for you, and part of that is to provide you with a consistent interface. And the aspect

00:03:21.160 --> 00:03:27.520
in tidy models that takes care of a consistent interface for models themselves is parsenet. So

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:33.960
it's designed to give you consistency both in how you specify and fit the model and how you

00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:41.639
predict and what you get back. So you don't have to remember function names, argument names across

00:03:41.639 --> 00:03:48.160
different packages, whether or not you get a vector back or a matrix or a data frame, and what that

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:55.559
type of prediction was called in this particular package you're using. And the thing I'm really

00:03:55.559 --> 00:04:03.039
here to talk about is censored, which is a parsenet extension package. So for survival models, so I'll

00:04:03.039 --> 00:04:09.960
be talking about how these design ideas play out and marry with survival analysis. Let's get to that

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:19.720
first part, to specify and fit models. In parsenet, you need three elements to specify your model. So

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:25.679
for one, the model type. In the example here, it's a random forest, and you need a computational

00:04:25.679 --> 00:04:31.839
engine. That's what you use to fit the model. My example here, that's the Ranger package. Often

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:37.119
that's various R packages. It can also be tools outside of R, like Stan, if you have a Bayesian

00:04:37.119 --> 00:04:45.079
model you want to fit. And the third element to a parsenet model specification is the mode. A random

00:04:45.079 --> 00:04:52.440
forest can be used for regression, for classification, so you need to specify that here. And these three

00:04:52.440 --> 00:05:02.000
elements are sort of very consistent in parsenet, so they will also show up in censored. So what is

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.279
actually new with censored? Well, we have to make a few additions. For one, we have a new model type,

00:05:08.279 --> 00:05:16.359
called proportional hazards, to let you fit everyone's favorite Cox model. Second of all,

00:05:16.359 --> 00:05:23.640
we have a new mode to distinguish censored regression from regression. And thirdly, you

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:30.359
probably guessed it, several new engines to existing models. So with that, censored covers

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:36.119
parametric models, semi-parametric models, and tree-based models for survival analysis. And the

00:05:36.119 --> 00:05:41.600
last point that I want to mention here is that we have a formula interface for all of these models.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:49.600
Most of the engines do that already, the glimnet package sort of famously does not, but we let you

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:54.839
interact with that through a formula interface, and that includes a way to specify stratification.

00:05:54.839 --> 00:06:03.880
And that's all sort of abstract, and I wanted to have a data example. Sadly, I do not have access

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:11.160
to that newspaper data, but I bring you dolphins and whales. So these are dolphins and whales living

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:17.480
in captivity in the U.S., whether they've been captured or rescued or were born in captivity.

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:25.959
It's originally a tidy Tuesday data set, all the way from the pudding. And we have the response

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:36.119
age in the first column, how old that dolphin is or was. If event is zero, the dolphin or whale is

00:06:36.119 --> 00:06:42.519
still alive. And we know the species, the sex, and how many times this animal was transferred

00:06:42.519 --> 00:06:49.799
between different facilities in the U.S. So if we want to go fit that brand new model, the

00:06:49.799 --> 00:06:56.279
proportional hazards model and tidy models, we need censored, and we need the proportional

00:06:56.279 --> 00:07:03.239
hazards function, and then we can add an engine. I'm going to go with the very classic survival

00:07:03.239 --> 00:07:08.040
package here as the way to fit this model. I'm going to add the mode. That's the new

00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:13.239
sensory regression mode. And with that, I have like the specification. This is not fit yet.

00:07:13.239 --> 00:07:18.920
If I want to apply it to data, I have a fit function, and that's where the formula interface

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:24.839
comes into place. Your response is typically a server object on the left-hand side of the formula.

00:07:24.839 --> 00:07:33.640
And you want to add stratification. You can do that like you would do in the survival package

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:40.760
and add a strata term into the formula. You're looking at this and saying, well,

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:46.279
that's plenty of lines of code for a model. That is indeed true. So if you

00:07:47.399 --> 00:07:51.720
work with the survival package directly, that's all a little bit condensed.

00:07:52.679 --> 00:07:58.519
Just the modeling function, the formula, and the data, that sort of does specification and fit all

00:07:58.519 --> 00:08:09.239
roll into one. And that's great. Where sort of censored comes more into play is if you want to

00:08:09.239 --> 00:08:17.720
use something else in addition to try it out and move between different models. So if we want to go

00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:23.720
from sort of the standard proportional hazards model to a regularized version of that model,

00:08:25.239 --> 00:08:28.519
I'm going to move all of the code to the left and start doing that with the

00:08:28.519 --> 00:08:33.719
columnar package on the right. That one has no formula interface, as I mentioned.

00:08:34.599 --> 00:08:40.200
So you need to make your response matrix and the predictor matrix.

00:08:41.719 --> 00:08:46.119
I'm doing that with model matrix here. And if you want to include stratification,

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:53.239
you need to stratify your response. And then you're ready to go. Put it into Glemnet. Remember

00:08:53.239 --> 00:08:58.840
to set the family to Fox. Otherwise, you're fitting a different model. And give it a penalty parameter

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:07.320
lambda. So of course, this is doable. But the code looks quite different, and it's quite a lot of work

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:15.080
to go from one to another. And we want to make that aspect easier. So obviously, the next code

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:21.880
is a little boring. You can take the bit that we already had for a censored and copy it over.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:29.320
And then the main thing you change is what engine you set. One is the survival package,

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:35.719
one is Glemnet. And the other thing you want to change is the penalty parameter, because it's

00:09:35.719 --> 00:09:41.400
Glemnet. But the rest is the same. So we don't have to fiddle with the data structure here.

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:48.119
We can still use the formula in this. And if you want to switch to yet another type,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:54.440
the tagline for that is kind of more models, same syntax. So you might swap out your model type for

00:09:54.440 --> 00:10:01.799
a boosted tree and set the engine to nboost, and you're ready to go. And that applies to the rest.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:09.719
We have in censored for that new mode, censored regression, the parametric models in the survival

00:10:09.719 --> 00:10:16.280
reg function, proportional hazards, or semi-parametric, and then the tree-based models

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:20.760
are decision trees, random forests, bag trees, and boosted trees you just saw.

00:10:21.880 --> 00:10:28.919
And that's the section on specifying and fitting. And the next one is obviously predicting.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:37.159
And in the tidy models framework, we give you a little guarantee that your predictions will

00:10:37.159 --> 00:10:43.400
always be inside a table. And the column names and types are unsurprising and predictable.

00:10:44.039 --> 00:10:52.679
And the number of rows in new data and the output are the same. So what's new then?

00:10:54.039 --> 00:10:59.559
Answer is new prediction types. One of them for survival analysis is the survival time.

00:11:00.359 --> 00:11:04.200
So I'm just taking the first three rows here of my data set to predict on them,

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:10.280
adding in an A in the first row just to mix things up a little, and you can get a prediction

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:16.760
of the survival time by using the predict function and setting type to time. And you get a table back,

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:22.440
the column will always be dot pride underscore time, and it will have three rows because you put

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:29.799
three rows in. So if you have a missing value, it will have an A rather than miraculously disappear

00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:39.080
on you. And the other big new type for survival predictions is the survival probability.

00:11:42.039 --> 00:11:48.520
That is always calculated at a point in time. So here in this example, I'm setting type survival,

00:11:49.239 --> 00:11:54.280
and I want the survival probability at age 10, 15, 20, and 40 years.

00:11:55.239 --> 00:12:03.239
Dolphin or whale that I'm looking at. And what you get back is still a table that has three rows

00:12:03.239 --> 00:12:09.960
for the three observations, but we've asked for four time points. So this is actually a list column

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:16.039
and it has little tables stashed inside of it. If we want to look at one of them, we can pull it out

00:12:16.039 --> 00:12:20.599
and then we see the column that gives us the information about the time point that we're

00:12:20.599 --> 00:12:26.039
predicting on and the probability, except for in this case it's an A, but if you look at the other

00:12:26.039 --> 00:12:36.760
one, you do get actual probabilities. And this does not return you like a classical serve object,

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:45.960
serve fit object. If you do want to access the full survival curve, you can pretty easily just

00:12:46.599 --> 00:12:51.960
dial up the number of time points you ask for. So here I'm asking for survival probability

00:12:51.960 --> 00:12:58.919
predicted at age one all the way through 80, and then I can unnest that thing to sort of

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:05.880
tag all the little tables underneath each other and I'm squeezing in the mutate to be still able

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:11.159
to tell which rows belong to which dolphin. And that gives you a data set that is ready for

00:13:12.039 --> 00:13:21.320
ggplot and you can easily do your visualization of the survival curve with a geom step.

00:13:22.919 --> 00:13:33.000
So to recap, the prediction types that are new are time or survival time and survival for survival

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:39.000
probability. These are available for all of the models that are uncensored and depending on the

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.440
engine you might also be able to break the hazard, the quantile of the event time distribution,

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:50.679
or the linear predictor if your model has one. You do not have to do any of like the data prepped

00:13:50.679 --> 00:13:54.840
for a matrix interface, you don't have to pad your results at the right place if there's a

00:13:54.840 --> 00:14:00.679
missing value in there, and you also don't have to do the lag work to go from a survival curve

00:14:00.679 --> 00:14:09.479
to predicted probability at like any given time point. And the summary of this all is basically

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:16.280
censored is a consistent interface for survival models. It gives you consistency in how you

00:14:16.280 --> 00:14:23.159
specify fit and consistency in how you predict and what you get back. So please try it out.

