Maybe one more question. What is the difference between stratifying on a variable in the survival

00:17:19.800 --> 00:17:28.760
model and using that variable as a predictor? So stratification in a Cox model gives you the

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:36.280
idea that the baseline hazard is different between groups, and that is sort of the non-parametric

00:17:36.280 --> 00:17:41.479
part, the baseline, and your predictors are the parametric part that modulate it.

00:17:41.479 --> 00:17:48.599
And if you think that this baseline hazard is not proportional between groups but rather

00:17:48.599 --> 00:17:51.959
fundamentally different, then you would put that into stratification.

